- ## CQRS
#CQRS #Terminology 
The Reactive Manifesto emphasizes  the need to build scalable, responsive  systems. It defines a reactive applica- tion’s basic traits: a message-driven  approach, elasticity, resiliency, and  responsiveness. It also suggests suit- able techniques for achieving them.  According to the manifesto, this leads  to more flexible, loosely coupled,  scalable, and failure-tolerant systems.

- ## CQRS
#CQRS #Terminology 
Our architecture conforms to the ba- sic traits mentioned in the Reactive  Manifesto. First, it’s message-driven.  Commands trigger events, which  trigger model updates. Second, it’s elastic. Adding new  write- and read-model instances im- proves performance; the event store  is built on top of scalable data stores. Third, it’s resilient. Losing an  instance of a write or read model  doesn’t prevent the system from  working. The lost instance can be  easily recreated; the event store uses  data stores with enabled replication. Finally, it’s responsive. The system  resolves user queries quickly because  it employs the best-performing query  models we could design. Aggregates  in the write model are completely  independent and easy to cache,  which improves command resolution  performance. The event store is  highly optimized for append-only op- erations and fetching events for a sin- gle aggregate. Implementation Details To build the application using the re- active approach, we used the Akka  toolkit (akka.io). It provides middle- ware that facilitates communication  between entities in the system in a  message-passing style. It implements  the actor model6 introduced many  years ago by Carl Hewitt and pop- ularized by the Erlang community.  The toolkit provides such useful  capabilities as cluster membership  service, actor location transparency,  different routing strategies, supervi- sion of actors, and implementation  of the Reactive Streams specification.

- ## Aggregates
#Aggregates #CQRS #Terminology 
An aggregate is a group of ap- plication entities that can’t be mu- tated independently. Conversely, all  the operations involving multiple  aggregate instances are performed  in an independent and eventually  consistent manner. That means the  smaller the aggregates, the higher  the concurrency level and the lower  the cost of performing a single  transaction. However, it also means  the invariants the system can hold  with strong consistency will be less  powerful.

- ## Aggregates
#Aggregates #CQRS #Terminology 
Aggregates in the system are  event-sourced; that is, they accept  commands, validate them, produce  events, persist them in the event  store, and finally transition to a new  state. When an aggregate is fetched,  a brand new instance is created, and  all the associated events are replayed  from the event store. Event ordering  is maintained only in a single aggre- gate.

- ## Read
#Read #Model #CQRS #Terminology 
The read model implements the con- straint checks regarding continuity  in rotations, the standard ground  time, and flight numbers. These vali- dations require quick graph-traversal  operations. We initially considered  an in-memory-only model but fi- nally decided that a graph-oriented  database is the most effective data  representation owing to the types of  queries and checks in our model. All  events processed in the read model  from the event store are transformed  to fit this model. We achieve scalable processing by  replicating the read-model instances  and balancing their load. Each node  manages its own database instance  with a complete model. When the  read side needs more processing  power, a new instance of a read  model is spawned. We avoid compli- cated model cloning; a new instance  can recreate the current state on its  own by asking the event store for the  complete history of events. When  the replay is over, the node joins  the load-balancer group to begin  Command 2 Command 3 WM1 WM2 Shard region service Event Cache Cache Cache store 1 2 3 4 5 6 WM3 Commands Command 1 FIGURE 2. The responsible node looks up its cache (step 5) and either returns the cached aggregate or constructs a new  instance using past events from the event store. - ## Event
#Event #Sourcing #Terminology 
CQRS meshes well with ES, an  advanced version of the Commit- Log pattern, well known to data- base designers and now considered a  mature method of managing persis- tence. System behavior is modeled in  terms of facts (events) happening in  the system and state machines, not  just the state representation (see Fig- ure 1b). This enables abandonment  of the object-relational mapping to  deliver a fully persistence-agnostic  model of the system. Moreover,  this approach automatically pro- vides a complete audit log of the  system. It’s especially useful when  combined with CQRS. New read  models can be added long after the  write model’s deployment, taking  into account the events stored thus  far. Users can change the shape of  projections (that is, how a stream of  events is converted into a structural  representation) and simply recreate  them from scratch. Such a commit  log might rely on storage that sup- ports append- only operations, usu- ally called an event store.
